And there'll be a line there.

00:01:43.620 --> 00:01:45.162
So if you're interested
in the books,

00:01:45.162 --> 00:01:47.070
you can go out my
left, your right.

00:01:47.070 --> 00:01:51.930
If you're not, then you go out
that way just to keep it going.

00:01:51.930 --> 00:01:55.050
I also want to say, for those
who haven't read this yet,

00:01:55.050 --> 00:01:58.672
this is a brilliant,
brilliant piece of work.

00:01:58.672 --> 00:02:00.630
One of things I try to
do is read all the books

00:02:00.630 --> 00:02:02.040
from our authors who come here.

00:02:02.040 --> 00:02:04.740
And this one was
just incredible.

00:02:04.740 --> 00:02:07.520
To take these four
presidents and weave

00:02:07.520 --> 00:02:11.533
through elements of their
lives is just majestic.

00:02:11.533 --> 00:02:13.950
But The New York Times, when
they were talking about this,

00:02:13.950 --> 00:02:16.860
they said quote,
"We can only hope

00:02:16.860 --> 00:02:18.900
that a few of
Goodwin's many readers

00:02:18.900 --> 00:02:22.710
will find in her subject
examples, a margin

00:02:22.710 --> 00:02:26.220
of inspiration and resolve to
steer the country to a better

00:02:26.220 --> 00:02:27.060
place."

00:02:27.060 --> 00:02:28.620
end quote.

00:02:28.620 --> 00:02:30.415
I also want to recognize
in the audience,

00:02:30.415 --> 00:02:33.570
and I'm not sure where
they are, but we have--

00:02:33.570 --> 00:02:35.310
one of the four
presidents this is about

00:02:35.310 --> 00:02:38.190
is, Theodore Roosevelt.
That Theodore Roosevelt's

00:02:38.190 --> 00:02:41.220
great grandson and his
son is with us tonight.

00:02:41.220 --> 00:02:43.387
So we're thrilled that
they're with us tonight.

