going to talk about.

00:04:19.540 --> 00:04:21.100
I just want to make one note.

00:04:21.100 --> 00:04:24.340
I just shrink and wince
when anything I've done

00:04:24.340 --> 00:04:28.570
is mentioned next to my fellow
New Yorker here, Doris Kearns

00:04:28.570 --> 00:04:29.130
Goodwin.

00:04:29.130 --> 00:04:31.180
But I have to change
the website, Steve.

00:04:31.180 --> 00:04:34.690
Because I think I
wrote that 25 years

00:04:34.690 --> 00:04:38.100
in broadcasting 15 years ago.

00:04:38.100 --> 00:04:40.900
I kind of like it.

00:04:40.900 --> 00:04:44.350
Doris, we spoke about
your extraordinary book

00:04:44.350 --> 00:04:47.890
a couple of months ago at your
beautiful home in Concord.

00:04:47.890 --> 00:04:50.990
And at the time, I mean, who's
read the book so we know.

00:04:50.990 --> 00:04:52.240
Plenty of people have read it.

00:04:52.240 --> 00:04:55.330
Oh, but plenty are
still in for a treat.

00:04:55.330 --> 00:04:56.830
And what you do
throughout the book

00:04:56.830 --> 00:04:58.780
is talk about the things
that shape these four

00:04:58.780 --> 00:05:03.280
extraordinary leaders, LBJ, FDR,
Teddy Roosevelt, and Lincoln.

00:05:03.280 --> 00:05:06.700
And they included things like
suffering loss, but being

00:05:06.700 --> 00:05:10.660
burnished by it,
humility, an ability

00:05:10.660 --> 00:05:12.550
to have empathy for others.

00:05:12.550 --> 00:05:16.030
And the list goes
on, controlling

00:05:16.030 --> 00:05:17.880
impulses of negative emotions.

00:05:20.990 --> 00:05:23.830
And we have a president
today, who I mean,

00:05:23.830 --> 00:05:27.400
I'm going to say out loud
what he kind of said today

00:05:27.400 --> 00:05:30.640
in his press comments,
does none of these things,

00:05:30.640 --> 00:05:33.310
does not acknowledge
mistakes or losses.

00:05:33.310 --> 00:05:35.230
Today he said that
the midterms were

00:05:35.230 --> 00:05:36.820
complete victory,
almost complete

00:05:36.820 --> 00:05:38.440
victory for the Republicans.

00:05:38.440 --> 00:05:42.610
They did quite well but
not a complete victory.

00:05:42.610 --> 00:05:45.070
The empathy, he was asked
during the press conference

00:05:45.070 --> 00:05:49.990
today about mentioning a
caravan that's 800 miles away

00:05:49.990 --> 00:05:55.230
and a, divisive language, and
he literally said, well, we won.

00:05:55.230 --> 00:05:59.100
He and his supporters
would say, hogwash.

00:05:59.100 --> 00:06:02.130
My way is working.

00:06:02.130 --> 00:06:08.030
His way is not this
way and it is working.

00:06:08.030 --> 00:06:10.470
DORIS KEARNS GOODWIN: Whoa.

00:06:10.470 --> 00:06:13.260
You know I think it's
working in the short term.

00:06:13.260 --> 00:06:17.250
Because what he was able
to do during the election

00:06:17.250 --> 00:06:20.940
and then it stayed true in
the people who supported him

00:06:20.940 --> 00:06:23.760
this time is to
speak to people who

00:06:23.760 --> 00:06:26.250
had felt much like
the people felt

00:06:26.250 --> 00:06:29.550
at the turn of the 20th century,
that they'd been left out

00:06:29.550 --> 00:06:32.610
of the America that is here
today, and worried about where

00:06:32.610 --> 00:06:33.937
the America is going.

00:06:33.937 --> 00:06:35.520
I mean at the turn
of the 20th century

00:06:35.520 --> 00:06:38.455
it was so much of an echo
to what's happening now.

00:06:38.455 --> 00:06:40.080
The Industrial
Revolution had shaken up

00:06:40.080 --> 00:06:42.300
the economy much
like tech revolution

00:06:42.300 --> 00:06:43.860
and globalization
have done today.

00:06:43.860 --> 00:06:45.270
For the first
time, there's a gap

00:06:45.270 --> 00:06:46.790
between the rich and the poor.

00:06:46.790 --> 00:06:50.190
The working class feel cut off
from the plenty of the country.

00:06:50.190 --> 00:06:52.140
There's a fear of immigration.

00:06:52.140 --> 00:06:55.170
And there's a sense in the
turn of the 20th century

00:06:55.170 --> 00:06:56.920
that a revolution was coming.

00:06:56.920 --> 00:06:59.303
But we had a leader
then in Teddy Roosevelt,

00:06:59.303 --> 00:07:01.470
who was able to channel
that populist emotion, which

00:07:01.470 --> 00:07:06.150
was anti-immigrant, anti-elite,
into reform, the Square

00:07:06.150 --> 00:07:08.940
Deal for the rich and
the poor, the wage

00:07:08.940 --> 00:07:10.560
worker and the capitalist.

00:07:10.560 --> 00:07:12.480
And what's happened
with President Trump

00:07:12.480 --> 00:07:16.090
is he got those people to feel
that he was on their side.

00:07:16.090 --> 00:07:19.800
And the polarization in this
country is really at a height,

00:07:19.800 --> 00:07:22.150
I mean longer than
in my lifetime.

00:07:22.150 --> 00:07:24.570
I mean, maybe not as long as
in the lifetime of the people

00:07:24.570 --> 00:07:27.408
that I've lived with, because
it's not as bad as the 1850s.

00:07:27.408 --> 00:07:28.950
And I think it's
important for people

00:07:28.950 --> 00:07:30.510
to feel, everybody
keeps asking me,

00:07:30.510 --> 00:07:32.280
are these the worst of times?

00:07:32.280 --> 00:07:34.320
And they feel like an
unmoored time right

00:07:34.320 --> 00:07:38.190
now, because of the lack of a
discernible political truth,

00:07:38.190 --> 00:07:41.960
because of lies and fake news
and a fight with the press that

00:07:41.960 --> 00:07:43.710
is unprecedented, the
enemy of the people,

00:07:43.710 --> 00:07:46.260
even as this press
conference happened today.

00:07:46.260 --> 00:07:48.570
But we have lived through
worse times before.

00:07:48.570 --> 00:07:50.910
And I think it's important
to get that perspective,

00:07:50.910 --> 00:07:54.060
so that we don't feel like we
can't get out of these times.

00:07:54.060 --> 00:07:57.060
I mean, if you lived
with Lincoln at the time

00:07:57.060 --> 00:07:58.832
when he comes into
office in 1861,

00:07:58.832 --> 00:08:00.540
there's going to be
a civil war that will

00:08:00.540 --> 00:08:02.520
kill more than 600,000 people.

00:08:02.520 --> 00:08:03.990
He never thought,
he said, he could

00:08:03.990 --> 00:08:05.907
have lived through the
anxiety if he had known

00:08:05.907 --> 00:08:07.290
what would be ahead of time.

00:08:07.290 --> 00:08:09.630
And Teddy Roosevelt's time
was even more tumultuous

00:08:09.630 --> 00:08:11.990
than this one is for
some of the same reasons.

00:08:11.990 --> 00:08:14.790
And the early days of the
Depression, if you're there

00:08:14.790 --> 00:08:17.200
and you're not sure
that the banks are even

00:08:17.200 --> 00:08:20.038
going to continue, because
they've taken your money

00:08:20.038 --> 00:08:21.330
and put it in the stock market.

00:08:21.330 --> 00:08:24.040
And some of them have money
but they don't believe they do.

00:08:24.040 --> 00:08:27.690
So there's a sense of not being
able to deal with your money.

00:08:27.690 --> 00:08:30.510
There's loss of jobs and
people who are hungry.

00:08:30.510 --> 00:08:31.860
And yet we got through that.

00:08:31.860 --> 00:08:36.088
And even when LBJ comes in,
it's the assassination of JFK,

00:08:36.088 --> 00:08:38.380
and there's not a clear idea
of where it's coming from.

00:08:38.380 --> 00:08:40.020
So the country was in shock.

00:08:40.020 --> 00:08:41.789
And yet we had the
right leaders and we

00:08:41.789 --> 00:08:44.250
had citizens who
were awakened, who

00:08:44.250 --> 00:08:45.930
became part of the
struggle, which

00:08:45.930 --> 00:08:49.330
is what is the hopeful thing
to me about this election

00:08:49.330 --> 00:08:50.610
yesterday.

00:08:50.610 --> 00:08:52.970
In each one of the
cases that I've studied,

00:08:52.970 --> 00:08:55.920
it was the citizens who
created a movement that allowed

00:08:55.920 --> 00:08:57.150
the leaders to go forward.

00:08:57.150 --> 00:08:58.880
The antislavery
movement, Lincoln said,

00:08:58.880 --> 00:09:00.180
was more important
than what he did.

00:09:00.180 --> 00:09:00.722
Without them.

00:09:00.722 --> 00:09:01.830
He couldn't have done it.

00:09:01.830 --> 00:09:04.410
The progressive movement
was essential for both Teddy

00:09:04.410 --> 00:09:07.350
and Franklin and the civil
rights movement for LBJ.

00:09:07.350 --> 00:09:08.940
We saw an awakening yesterday.

00:09:08.940 --> 00:09:11.130
We saw people standing
on long lines.

00:09:11.130 --> 00:09:15.090
We saw hosts of new
women coming into office

00:09:15.090 --> 00:09:18.150
for the first time who had not
been in public life before.

00:09:18.150 --> 00:09:22.840
[APPLAUSE]

00:09:22.840 --> 00:09:25.930
We all saw a host of veterans
coming into office too.

00:09:25.930 --> 00:09:29.410
And I think what that means
is that somethings, there's

00:09:29.410 --> 00:09:31.450
a fever that has to be
broken and something's

00:09:31.450 --> 00:09:34.390
been really wrong in Washington
for a long period of time.

00:09:34.390 --> 00:09:36.400
And people coming
into public life now

00:09:36.400 --> 00:09:38.560
means they still
believe in politics.

00:09:38.560 --> 00:09:41.810
They still believe that politics
can be as JFK wanted it to be,

00:09:41.810 --> 00:09:45.290
an honorable profession, so
that's a really good sign.

00:09:45.290 --> 00:09:49.570
So I think as polarizing as the
election was and how it still

00:09:49.570 --> 00:09:52.930
is going to produce a
divided House and a Senate,

00:09:52.930 --> 00:09:55.690
if the citizens are awakened
and if the people are

00:09:55.690 --> 00:09:58.300
the ultimate check on what's
going on right now, if they

00:09:58.300 --> 00:10:02.110
exercise their power, not just
to vote but to be citizens that

00:10:02.110 --> 00:10:03.830
are active instead
of spectators,

00:10:03.830 --> 00:10:04.900
we're going to be OK.

00:10:04.900 --> 00:10:07.150
ROBIN YOUNG: Well, and I'm
glad you mentioned the word

